<h1 id="trust-and-risk"><a id="TrustAndRisk"></a>Trust and Risk</h1>

<p>Every Cyber attack is a <strong>breach of trust</strong>. Most systems that humans create all rely on trust to work (you trust that the rules of chess you are playing by are the same as your opponent).</p>

<h2 id="commitment">Commitment</h2>

<p>What if we can‚Äôt trust the other party, sometimes we can use the idea of commitment to make sure that people stick to their word.</p>

<p>Here are some problems that can be fixed with commitment:</p>
<ul>
  <li>I‚Äôve finished my exam paper at the correct time, but the internet went out and I can‚Äôt email the exam. How can I submit my exam later and have people trust that its the same exam as when i ended</li>
  <li>I‚Äôm on the phone with someone who is flipping a coin. If I tell them my side, they can claim the coin landed on the other side. How can i commit to a side without letting the other person know, when make sure that when i reveal the side later, its the same as before the coin was tossed.</li>
</ul>

<p>Commitment can be done by hashing the message, sending the hash when you make the commitment. Later, send the actual message and other parties can check the hashes are the same, hence trust your message. This both makes sure that others can‚Äôt seem the message (due to the one way-ness of hashes) before a certain time, AND others can trust that we didn‚Äôt change our message after being revealed.</p>

<p>There are a few flaws that need fixing:</p>
<ul>
  <li>What if we memories the hashes of things like ‚Äúheads‚ÄĚ and ‚Äútails‚ÄĚ</li>
  <li>What if i brute force both ‚Äúheads‚ÄĚ and ‚Äútails‚ÄĚ with a random number at the end so that they have the same hash.</li>
</ul>

<p>To fix these problems, we usually <strong>sandwich the message with 2 random numbers decided by each parties</strong> so that a brute force is impossible, and hashes are unmemorable.</p>

<h2 id="risk">Risk</h2>

<p>One way that we can think about risk, is <strong>Risk vs Reward</strong>, There are a few problems with risk that are important to take into account:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Risk is invisible, but outcomes are not</strong>! This causes humans to be very bad at analyzing risk and making appropriate decisions. When you get away with a risk, it‚Äôs only really luck that let you get away with it, but you are the same person the person who happened to get the bad end of the risk stick</li>
  <li><strong>Risk changes base on our experiences</strong>, after experiencing the consequences of the risk, humans seem to have a different equation of risk vs reward, but the situation is exactly the same.
    <ul>
      <li>this can sometimes be a good thing, <strong>if taking risks lead to learning about our mistakes, then taking the risk was a good for our understanding of the consequences</strong>.</li>
      <li>this is the main reason why humans are terrible at low probability, high risk situation, we don‚Äôt have enough collective experience with the consequence to properly understand the risk vs reward equation.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

